@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@divergence The canonical pattern deepens this via Sen (temporal
conversion), whole-board-play (iteration as prerequisite for
competence), and Ostrom (provisioning problem).  The paper is
narrower: breadth-vs-depth tension, impostor syndrome, and a specific
resolution (declared delivery profile, treating institutional coverage
as a network property).  This variant records the paper's framing.

! conclusion: The breadth of open-research topics exceeds what any single trainer can confidently cover.  The resolution is to let each trainer declare a delivery profile — the modules they will own — and for the programme to treat institutional coverage as a network property across its trainers rather than a requirement of each individual.  Each institution commits an explicit profile of its coverage aims and resourcing.
  + context: This is NPT Collective Action — specifically 3.3 Skill Set Workability and 3.4 Contextual Integration.  It is an intervention-tier pattern with medium coordination, requiring two formal actors: the Training Project and the Institutional Lead (or other local representative).  Where weak coordination leaves the trainer absorbing the gap alone, the pattern produces absorbed input; where team-working is supported, trainers grow in competence and the pattern contributes to multiplied input.
  + IF:
    A programme trains intermediaries who deliver open-research topics spanning a wide territory (statistics, data management, software, publication practices, ethics, reproducibility, etc.).  Delivery depends on the trainer's capacity to cover the territory competently — but the territory is broader than any single trainer's primary expertise, and many trainers are professional staff delivering outside their primary discipline.
  + HOWEVER:
    The breadth produces a breadth-versus-depth tension compounded by impostor syndrome.  Trainers report feeling inadequately prepared (FG1.15, FG2A.13; FG3.13, FG2A.4).  Sessions attempt to cover too much and lose interaction depth (T1: "give it more time than you expect"; T2B.17: delivers only a fraction of material learned; T2A: "I didn't feel prepared to talk about all the areas"; T3: "There's a little bit of impostor syndrome, because it's still new to me and no one's taught me it!").  COM-B "I am psychologically able" M=4.85, high individually, but the breadth gap is structural: trainers silently absorb a coordination problem that extends beyond their remit.
  + THEN:
    Each trainer declares a delivery profile — the modules they will own.  The programme treats institutional coverage as a network property across its trainers, not a requirement of each individual.  Each participating institution commits an explicit profile of its coverage aims and the resourcing (time, scope, team support) that matches.  Coverage becomes a visible distribution across the network rather than an invisible overload on each trainer.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT Collective Action: 3.3 Skill Set Workability is the fit between what the work demands and what the trainer can reasonably do; 3.4 Contextual Integration is the fit between the work and its institutional context.  Breadth overload breaks both.  Named profiles restore the fit at both levels.

    Two-actor coordination: The pattern cannot be resolved by the Training Project alone — the institution must name a coverage profile and resource it.  Coordination rises from Low (Pattern 1) to Medium.  The Institutional Lead (or Local Network Lead in the post-ORP setting) is the second formal actor.

    Network-property framing: Treating coverage as a network property is a structural move, not an operational one.  It reframes what the programme is asking of any single trainer — not "cover everything" but "own a declared subset, with coverage guaranteed across the network."  This is what prevents trainers from silently absorbing the coordination problem.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Ask each trainer to declare the modules they will own
    - Ask each institution to commit an explicit coverage profile with resourcing
    - Publish the aggregate coverage across the network so gaps are visible to the programme, not only to individual trainers
    - Audit breadth-vs-depth in sessions: where a trainer is covering outside their declared profile, surface that to the Institutional Lead
    - Test: can every trainer point to the modules they own and know which modules a colleague owns?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Each trainer has a declared delivery profile.  Each participating institution has a committed coverage profile with named resourcing.  The programme maintains a current view of coverage as a network property.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Breadth overload: trainers silently cover topics outside their primary expertise without team support
    - Impostor-driven delivery: trainer reaches a session under-prepared because declaration was not possible
    - Un-profiled institutions: institution participates without naming what it covers or what it resources
    - Invisible coordination: coverage problem extends beyond the trainer's remit but is absorbed by the trainer alone
    - Per-trainer coverage requirement: the network's coverage is treated as an expectation of each individual rather than a distributed property
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 2: Protected Interaction
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("give it more time than you expect")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2A ("I didn't feel prepared to talk about all the areas")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("There's a little bit of impostor syndrome")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B.17 (delivers only a fraction of material learned)
    - Focus-group codes: FG1.15, FG2A.13 (impostor syndrome); FG3.13, FG2A.4 (professional-staff preparation)
    - COM-B: "I am psychologically able" M=4.85
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Collective Action 3.3 Skill Set Workability and 3.4 Contextual Integration as stated in the companion journal article.
    Tier: Intervention.  Coordination: Medium (programme + Institutional Lead).
    Implementation-mode link: weak coordination → absorbed input; supported team-working → contributes to multiplied input.
    The paper names a specific mechanism (delivery profile, institutional coverage as network property) that the canonical equity pattern renders more abstractly.
